1. Title: 1985 Auto Imports Database

2. Source Information:
   -- Creator/Donor: Jeffrey C. Schlimmer (Jeffrey.Schlimmer@a.gp.cs.cmu.edu)
   -- Date: 19 May 1987
   -- Sources:
     1) 1985 Model Import Car and Truck Specifications, 1985 Ward's
        Automotive Yearbook.
     2) Personal Auto Manuals, Insurance Services Office, 160 Water
        Street, New York, NY 10038 
     3) Insurance Collision Report, Insurance Institute for Highway
        Safety, Watergate 600, Washington, DC 20037

3. Past Usage:
   -- Kibler,~D., Aha,~D.~W., \& Albert,~M. (1989).  Instance-based prediction
      of real-valued attributes.  {\it Computational Intelligence}, {\it 5},
      51--57.
	 -- Predicted price of car using all numeric and Boolean attributes
	 -- Method: an instance-based learning (IBL) algorithm derived from a
	    localized k-nearest neighbor algorithm.  Compared with a
	    linear regression prediction...so all instances
	    with missing attribute values were discarded.  This resulted with
	    a training set of 159 instances, which was also used as a test
	    set (minus the actual instance during testing).
	 -- Results: Percent Average Deviation Error of Prediction from Actual
	    -- 11.84% for the IBL algorithm
	    -- 14.12% for the resulting linear regression equation

4. Relevant Information:
   -- Description
      This data set consists of three types of entities: (a) the
      specification of an auto in terms of various characteristics, (b)
      its assigned insurance risk rating, (c) its normalized losses in use
      as compared to other cars.  The second rating corresponds to the
      degree to which the auto is more risky than its price indicates.
      Cars are initially assigned a risk factor symbol associated with its
      price.   Then, if it is more risky (or less), this symbol is
      adjusted by moving it up (or down) the scale.  Actuarians call this
      process "symboling".  A value of +3 indicates that the auto is
      risky, -3 that it is probably pretty safe.

      The third factor is the relative average loss payment per insured
      vehicle year.  This value is normalized for all autos within a
      particular size classification (two-door small, station wagons,
      sports/speciality, etc...), and represents the average loss per car
      per year.

   -- Note: Several of the attributes in the database could be used as a
            "class" attribute.

5. Number of Instances: 205

6. Number of Attributes: 26 total
   -- 15 continuous
   -- 1 integer
   -- 10 nominal

7. Attribute Information:     
     Attribute:                Attribute Range:
     ------------------        -----------------------------------------------
  1. symboling:                -3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3. he higher the number, the more risky
                               the car is perceived to be by insurers.
  2. normalized-losses:        continuous from 65 to 256. Higher values mean more costly 
                               insurance losses (more claims or more expensive repairs)
  3. make:                     alfa-romero, audi, bmw, chevrolet, dodge, honda,
                               isuzu, jaguar, mazda, mercedes-benz, mercury,
                               mitsubishi, nissan, peugot, plymouth, porsche,
                               renault, saab, subaru, toyota, volkswagen, volvo
  4. fuel-type:                diesel, gas.
  5. aspiration:               std, turbo.(Standard): The engine pulls in air without forced
                               induction. Power output is limited by atmospheric pressure.
                               Uses a turbocharger to force more air into the combustion 
                               chamber, increasing engine power and performance, but typically
                               at the cost of fuel economy and complexity.
  6. num-of-doors:             four, two.
  7. body-style:               hardtop, wagon, sedan, hatchback, convertible.
                               hardtop:A fixed-roof car without a central B-pillar—gives a sleeker look
                               wagon:Extended rear cargo area, similar to a hatchback but longer
                               sedan:Traditional passenger car with separate trunk (most common car shape)
                               hatchback:Compact car with rear door that swings upward, cargo area is accessible
                               convertible:Roof can be folded down or removed (open-air driving)
  8. drive-wheels:             4wd, fwd, rwd.
  9. engine-location:          front, rear.
 10. wheel-base:               continuous from 86.6 120.9.  is the distance between the center of the 
                               front wheel and the center of the rear wheel.
                               Shorter (≈ 86–95)	More agile, often in compact/small cars
                               Longer (≈ 100–121)	More stable, smoother ride, larger interior
 11. length:                   continuous from 141.1 to 208.1.
 12. width:                    continuous from 60.3 to 72.3.
 13. height:                   continuous from 47.8 to 59.8.
 14. curb-weight:              continuous from 1488 to 4066.Curb weight is the weight of a fully assembled
                               car with standard equipment and necessary fluids (oil, coolant, full tank of fuel), 
                               but without passengers or baggage.
                               ~1500–2000 lbs	Light compact cars
                               ~2000–3000 lbs	Average sedans or hatchbacks
                               ~3000–4000+ lbs	Larger sedans, SUVs, performance cars
 15. engine-type:              dohc, dohcv, l, ohc, ohcf, ohcv, rotor.
                               dohc:Double Overhead Camshaft – Two camshafts in the cylinder head
                               dohcv:Double Overhead Camshaft (V-type) – DOHC engine in a V-configuration
                               l:L-head (flathead engine) – Older, less common design
                               ohc:Overhead Camshaft – One camshaft above the cylinder head
                               ohcf:Overhead Camshaft (flat configuration) – Variant of OHC in flat engines
                               ohcv:Overhead Camshaft (V-type) – OHC engine in V-type layout
                               rotor:Rotary engine – Uses a rotary design (e.g., Mazda Wankel engine)
 16. num-of-cylinders:         eight, five, four, six, three, twelve, two. More cylinders → Typically
                               more power, but lower fuel efficiency Fewer cylinders → Better fuel economy,
                               but less performance
 17. engine-size:              continuous from 61 to 326.
 18. fuel-system:              1bbl, 2bbl, 4bbl, idi, mfi, mpfi, spdi, spfi.
                               Carburetor types (1bbl, 2bbl, 4bbl) are older technologies.
                               Fuel injection types (mpfi, spfi, mfi) are more modern, offering better fuel 
                               efficiency and performance.
                               Diesel systems (idi, spdi) are found in diesel-engine vehicles.
 19. bore:                     continuous from 2.54 to 3.94.
                               Smaller (~2.5–3.0)	Smaller, fuel-efficient engines
                               Larger (~3.0–3.9+)	Larger, more powerful engines
 20. stroke:                   continuous from 2.07 to 4.17.
                               Shorter (≈ 2.0–3.0)	Higher RPM potential, better for speed/performance
                               Longer (≈ 3.0–4.2)	More torque, better fuel economy, smoother engine
 21. compression-ratio:        continuous from 7 to 23.
                               Lower (7–9)	Found in older or lower-performance engines; tolerates lower-octane fuel
                               Moderate (9–11)	Common in modern gasoline engines
                               Higher (12–23)	More efficient, higher power output; common in diesel engines or 
                               performance-tuned gasoline engines
 22. horsepower:               continuous from 48 to 288.
                               48–80 hp	Low-powered, economy cars (e.g., subcompacts)
                               81–150 hp	Average cars (e.g., sedans, hatchbacks)
                               151–220 hp	Mid- to high-performance vehicles
                               221–288 hp	Sports/luxury/performance vehicles
 23. peak-rpm:                 continuous from 4150 to 6600.
                               4150–5000	Low-revving engines, usually tuned for torque and fuel economy
                               5000–6000	Balanced performance – common in many modern engines
                               6000–6600	High-revving engines, optimized for sporty performance
 24. city-mpg:                 continuous from 13 to 49.
 25. highway-mpg:              continuous from 16 to 54.
 26. price:                    continuous from 5118 to 45400.

